
test_aes: Showcase basic encryption and decryption using the
          AES core via the Unified API

AEAD features and use of the key derivation core in conjunction with the
AES core are not supported in this container.

Load the container and see usage in logs:
$ mwtest.py -c100 run test_aes.img
$ cmtest log
<...>
CI: First message:   encrypt|decrypt MODE KEY [IV]
CI: Next message(s): DATA or unaligned/empty for final
CI: MODE:   ecb|cbc|cfb|ctr
CI: TAGLEN: Length of tag in bytes
CI: KEY:    string or 0x.. for hex data
CI: IV:     ascii or 0x.. for hex data
CI: DATA:   ascii or binary
CI:
CI: Note: DATA is unaligned iff length % 16 != 0
<...>

Examples (relevant cmtest log output is shown below commands)
-------------------------------------------------------------

1) Encrypting

$ cmtest data -f100 'encrypt cbc AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA BBBBBBBBBBBBBBBB'
CD: Performing cmrt_aes_init() with operation=0 mode=1 taglen=0 key=0x1028334 keylen=16 iv=0x1028344 ivlen=16

$ cmtest data -f100 "CCCCCCCCCCCCCCCC" > ./ciphertext
CI: Got request from HLOS of 16 bytes
CD: Request from HLOS:
CD:00000000 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 |CCCCCCCCCCCCCCCC|
CD: updatelen = 16 finallen = 0
CD: Doing cmrt_aes_update...
CI: Sending response to HLOS of 16 bytes
CD: Response to HLOS:
CD:00000000 aa 1a 18 ff 55 61 5f 61 22 f2 87 48 65 c8 1b fc |....Ua_a"..He...|
(note: this data is also sent to HLOS via SIC)

Since the data length was aligned we need to send an empty message to
finalize the operation.
Otherwise the container will keep expecting more data to encrypt.
$ cmtest data -f100 ''
CD: updatelen = 0 finallen = 0
CD: Doing cmrt_aes_final...
CI: Closing AES context
CI: Sending response to HLOS of 0 bytes

2) Decrypting
Let's decrypt the previously encrypted message.

$ cmtest data -f100 'decrypt cbc AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA BBBBBBBBBBBBBBBB'
CD: Performing cmrt_aes_init() with operation=1 mode=1 taglen=0 key=0x1028334 keylen=16 iv=0x1028344 ivlen=16

$ cmtest data -f100 ./ciphertext
CI: Got request from HLOS of 16 bytes
CD: Request from HLOS:
CD:00000000 aa 1a 18 ff 55 61 5f 61 22 f2 87 48 65 c8 1b fc |....Ua_a"..He...|
CD: updatelen = 16 finallen = 0
CD: Doing cmrt_aes_update...
CI: Sending response to HLOS of 16 bytes
CD: Response to HLOS:
CD:00000000 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 43 |CCCCCCCCCCCCCCCC|

$ cmtest data -f100 ''

Notes
-----

The container processes input in a loop. If a unified api call fails it will
exit.

Nothing special needs to be done to send more than one block. test_aes
processes all the data you send to it. Last block is padded with zero to the
blocksize if necessary.

You can see the logs to see when cmrt_aes_update() and cmrt_aes_final() are
called.

Running some AES KATs (Known Answer Tests)
------------------------------------------

KEY = 00000000000000000000000000000000         (16 bytes hex-encoded)
IV = 00000000000000000000000000000000
PLAINTEXT = ffffffffffffffe00000000000000000
CIPHERTEXT = d451b8d6e1e1a0ebb155fbbf6e7b7dc3

$ cmtest data -f100 'encrypt cbc 0x00000000000000000000000000000000 0x00000000000000000000000000000000'
$ printf 'ffffffffffffffe00000000000000000' | xxd -r -p > cleartext
$ cmtest data -f100 ./cleartext > ./ciphertext
...received 16 bytes OK
00000000: d4 51 b8 d6 e1 e1 a0 eb  b1 55 fb bf 6e 7b 7d c3  |.Q.......U..n{}.|

$ cmtest data -f100 'decrypt cbc 0x00000000000000000000000000000000 0x00000000000000000000000000000000'
$ cmtest data -f100 ./ciphertext
...received 16 bytes OK
00000000: ff ff ff ff ff ff ff e0  00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00  |................|

Same result as test vector expected output.


In the following lines you can find a few more AES KAT vectors.

mode ecb
KEY = 00000000000000000000000000000000
PLAINTEXT = ffffffffffffffe00000000000000000
CIPHERTEXT = d451b8d6e1e1a0ebb155fbbf6e7b7dc3

mode cfb
KEY = 00000000000000000000000000000000
IV = ffffffffffffffe00000000000000000
PLAINTEXT = 00000000000000000000000000000000
CIPHERTEXT = d451b8d6e1e1a0ebb155fbbf6e7b7dc3

Examples for AEAD modes
-----------------------

For AEAD modes like GCM, end-of-data is still signaled with either a last
message of length not multiple of 16 or with an empty message. The last
message is not padded with 0. The length of the ciphertext is exactly the
length of the cleartext.

For encrypt operations, the last response message contains appended the
authentication tag. If the last sent message is the empty message, the
response is exactly the authentication tag.

The start message (before the data message) needs to contain the tag (for
decrypt) or the tag length (for encrypt).

The AAD (additional authenticated data) has to be provided in its entirety in
the start message or provide a "-" meaning there is no AAD.

$ cmtest data -f100 "encrypt gcm 16 - 0xca7db9e97cfa056b80dcd04f46228640 0x5e8dc246ee835dc5f229d698"
                        taglen --^  ^-- no aad     ^-- key              iv --^
$ printf "964610fb6585cbbb070fd9ab10a7a600" | xxd -r -p > ./cleartext
$ cmtest data -f100 ./cleartext > ciphertext
$ cmtest data -f100 "" > tag

$ xxd -p ./tag
c633075a8b608d5f96971d2bc1ea2a0e
                                 !-- tag instead of taglen for "decrypt"
$ cmtest data -f100 "decrypt gcm 0xc633075a8b608d5f96971d2bc1ea2a0e - 0xca7db9e97cfa056b80dcd04f46228640 0x5e8dc246ee835dc5f229d698"
$ cmtest data -f100 ./ciphertext > decypted_text
$ cmtest data -f100 ""
$ xxd -p ./decrypted_text
964610fb6585cbbb070fd9ab10a7a600
$ cmp ./cleartext ./decrypted_text
$

If we repeat the same decryption but we corrupt the provided tag, the first
data message is decrypted successfully but the last empty message will
trigger an exit of the container because the last syscall fails with -5.

14:23:14,904: CE: cmrt_aes_final failed with -5

This means an authentication error.

Sending a single empty data message after the starts message is valid and it
represents an empty message. The tag is returned.

Examples for CMAC mode
----------------------

CMAC is a keyed hash. The container considers the end of input when either an
empty data message is received or a message whose length is not multiple of 16,
same as the normal cipher modes. However, only the last message will yield a
result via SIC, which is the fixed-size hash (16 bytes) of all the data.

$ cmtest data -f100 "cmac 0x41414141414141414141414141414141"
$ cmtest data -f100 "" > hash
$ xxd -p ./hash
1686dfe9b1609462ef3a6a4b3469b54a

$ cmtest data -f100 "cmac 0x41414141414141414141414141414141"
$ cmtest data -f100 "hello" > hash
$ xxd -p ./hash
ecebc53d3568d175b3c729bb77d3399b
